{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646248"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:28:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:28:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18168"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18168"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73707"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10882"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59180"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"},{"type":"tags","id":"7310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25312"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73707"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding the typical thoracic vertebrae?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The spinous processes are short","They are T1-T9","The transverse processes are short","The spinous processes are long and downward-sloping","The vertebral foramen is triangular and large"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe spinous processes are long and downward-sloping\u003C/strong\u003E is correct for typical thoracic vertebrae. This feature helps distinguish thoracic vertebrae from cervical and lumbar vertebrae, which have shorter spinous processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey are T1-T9\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Typical thoracic vertebrae are generally considered to be T2-T8, as T1 and T9-T12 have unique features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe vertebral foramen is triangular and large\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In thoracic vertebrae, the vertebral foramen is circular and smaller compared to cervical vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe spinous processes are short\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Thoracic vertebrae have long spinous processes that slope downward.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe transverse processes are short\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Thoracic vertebrae have longer transverse processes with facets for rib articulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Typical thoracic vertebrae are characterised by specific anatomical features that distinguish them from cervical and lumbar vertebrae.","The vertebral foramen in thoracic vertebrae is circular and smaller compared to cervical vertebrae.","Thoracic vertebrae have long, downward-sloping spinous processes.","The transverse processes of thoracic vertebrae are longer and have facets for rib articulation."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer